name: NATS - The Cloud Native Messaging System
description: NATS is an open-source, high-performance, lightweight and secure cloud native messaging system. NATS is a hosted CNCF project.
contribution_justification:
https://nats.io/contributing/
Describes filing bugs, issues, and pull requests for our GitHub repository
contribution_requirements_justification:
https://nats.io/contributing/
Code Review Criteria
Knowing what’s likely to be accepted or rejected and why is a key consideration in deciding whether and what to contribute. The criteria below are things we think about and look for in any proposed change. We have Performance, Stability, Simplicity, and Security in mind at all times.

Simply put, changes that have many or large positives, and few negative effects or risks, are much more likely to be merged, and merged quickly. Risky and less valuable changes are very unlikely to be merged, and may be rejected outright rather than receive iterations of review.

Pluses

Fixes the root cause of a bug in existing functionality
Adds functionality or fixes a problem needed by a large number of users
Simple, targeted
Maintains or improves consistency across supported API languages
Easily tested; has tests
Reduces complexity and lines of code
Change has already been discussed and is known to the committers

Minuses

Non-optional new functionality that negatively affects performance
Band-aids a symptom of a bug only
Introduces complex new functionality, especially an API that needs to be supported
Adds complexity that only helps a niche use case
Adds user-space functionality that does not need to be maintained as part of NATS
Changes a public API or semantics (rarely allowed)
Adds large dependencies
Changes versions of existing dependencies
Adds a large amount of code
Is not modular/targeted – makes lots of modifications in one “big bang” change
Breaks existing tests (implying your change is not backwards compatible)
Code coverage decreases (implying you didn’t add sufficient tests for new/changed code)

Version control on GitHub

repo_track_justification:
GitHub repo commits tracks changes, authors, and dates

release_notes_vulns_justification: Any CVE would be specific to the kernel (which is chosen by the end user) or the version of Go used to build the project which is also available to the user. When Go has a CVE we do issue new release binary builds with the newer version of Go as appropriate.
report_responses_justification: These are included in the release notes: https://github.com/nats-io/gnatsd/releases
vulnerability_report_process_justificati:
We encourage users to open issues with any know issues including vulnerabilities.
https://nats.io/documentation/contributing/
vulnerability_report_private_justificati:
This can be accomplished via direct email to the NATS.io team or direct message within the SLACK channel.
More information here https://nats.io/documentation/contributing/
build_common_tools_justification: Golang and Travis.CI for CI and releases. Releases hosted on GitHub.
build_floss_tools_justification: All tools required to build are OSS.
test_justification: Golang test suite with Travis.CI for the CI portion.
test_invocation_justification: NATS.io uses standard Go testing frameworks.
test_most_justification: We utilize code coverage, race detection and additional FLOSS checks like https://github.com/dominikh/go-tools. See https://github.com/nats-io/gnatsd/blob/master/.travis.yml for more information.
test_policy_justification: Tests and test coverage are required for any PRs.
tests_are_added_justification: We do not allow any changes to master without the code changes having test coverage.
tests_documented_added_justification:
It is part of the PR template system.
https://github.com/nats-io/gnatsd/blob/master/.github/PULL_REQUEST_TEMPLATE.md
warnings_strict_justification: No releases are made that do not pass all tests which include `go vet` and megacheck.
crypto_published_justification: Utilize TLS as implemented and defined by Go programming language. We do allow users to select preferences for the ciphers.
crypto_call_justification: All clients use language supplied TLS or bcrypt as provided by Google for Golang.
crypto_pfs_justification: All session keys are within the TLS implementation of the language provider.
crypto_password_storage_justification: We provide for Bcrypt and are moving towards no passwords. We do still allow plaintext passwords for backward compatibility, however this will be deprecated soon.
crypto_random_justification: We utilize crypto/rand and all crypto PRNGs.
delivery_unsigned_justification: We do not currently utilize cryptographic hashes.
vulnerabilities_fixed_60_days_justificat: Users choose the kernel so we are not able to do much about that, but we do upgrade the version of Go for any CVEs within 60 days.
static_analysis_fixed_justification: No code can be released that does not pass all tests and analyzers.
dynamic_analysis_justification:
We have not run any fuzzers or other dynamic analysis yet.
https://groups.google.com/d/msg/golang-dev/m0Q60EEydX0/pRBY6BrShqcJ
dynamic_analysis_unsafe_justification: No memory unsafe code is used in the released binaries of gnatsd.
dynamic_analysis_enable_assertions_justi: Golang includes runtime assertions such as boundary checks and index checks for slices and arrays.
dynamic_analysis_fixed_justification: Do not run any formal dynamic code analysis.
crypto_weaknesses_justification: We utilize all the top recommended ciphers for TLS 1.2+ and will move to TLS 1.3 shortly. We also utilize BCrypt from Google.
test_continuous_integration_justificatio: Travis tests are automatically run on any changes to master and all branches known by Github for the NATS.io Organization.
discussion_justification:
Various communication methods e.g. GitHub, GoogleGroups, StackOverflow, Slack
More information on contribution and discussion at https://nats.io/contributing/
english_justification: Information available in English regarding contributing with bugs, issues, PR here https://nats.io/contributing/

Feedback: https://prosody.im/bugs and https://prosody.im/discuss
Contribute: https://prosody.im/doc/contributing

floss_license_osi_justification: The MIT license is approved by the Open Source Initiative (OSI).
documentation_basics_justification: https://prosody.im/doc
documentation_interface_justification:
Prosody's internal API is documented at https://prosody.im/doc/developers
XMPP is documented in RFCs 6120, 6121 and in extensions published by the XMPP Standards Foundation at https://xmpp.org/extensions/
repo_distributed_justification: Mercurial is a common version control system used by many projects.
report_responses_justification: >90% of issues between March 2018 and March 2019 were acknowledged (including fixed or closed).
enhancement_responses_justification: >60% of feature requests between March 2018 and March 2019 were acknowledged (including implemented or closed).
vulnerability_report_private_justificati: Reports are accepted via private email, documented at https://prosody.im/bugs/
build_justification: Automatic nightly builds are available at https://packages.prosody.im/nightly/
test_justification: Both unit and integration tests are provided in the repository, under spec/.
test_invocation_justification: There is no official standard for Lua, but Prosody uses 'busted', a common testing tool for Lua.
test_most_justification: We are increasing test coverage all the time, however coverage is currently below 50% of the overall codebase (with a focus on ensuring algorithms and complex areas are correct).
tests_documented_added_justification: Currently there is no documented test policy, however we expect this to change.
warnings_justification: We compile C code with `-Wall` and all Lua code is run through `luacheck` as part of our automated testing.
static_analysis_common_vulnerabilities_j: Many of the issues luacheck scans for may be precursors to vulnerabilities, but luacheck does not specifically scan for vulnerabilities. No such tool exists for Lua.
dynamic_analysis_justification: Not currently performed. There are no fuzzing tools specifically aimed at Lua, but some of the generic ones may be adaptable given some work.
dynamic_analysis_unsafe_justification: Our C libraries only expose a Lua interface, and thus the above applies.
test_continuous_integration_justificatio: Buildbot automatically build after code changes: https://buildbot.prosody.im/
